Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium high heat. Slice open the @97% pork sausages{250%g}, remove the meat and discard the skin. Shape your sausage meat into balls about 2cm in diameter. Add them to your frying pan and cook until browned, ~{10-12%minutes}. Turn them regularly to make sure they don't burn.

Halve, then remove the core from the @bell pepper{1} and thinly slice. Chop each @dried apricots{40%g} into four pieces. Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}. Pick the @mint{1}(leaves picked from stalks and roughly chopped) and roughly chop(discard the stalks).

Add the pepper to the meatballs. Cook until soft, ~{5-7%minutes}. Stir in the @ras-el-hanout{1%tsp} and dried apricots, cook for ~{1%minute} and then pour in the @tomato passata{1%400g jar}. Add the @water{200%ml}, chickpeas, half the @chicken stock powder{1/2%tbsp} and stir to dissolve. Bring to the boil, turn the heat to medium low and simmer the sauce until thick and reduced by half, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Pour the @water{300%ml} into a large #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, stir in the remaining @chicken stock powder{1/2%tbsp} and the @couscous{150%g}, pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{8-10%minutes} or until ready to serve. The couscous will cook and absorb the stock while you get everything else done.

When your stew is ready, taste and add @salt{} and @black pepper{} if necessary.

> The meatballs are cooked when they are no longer pink in the middle.

Stir in the @baby spinach{125%g} and cook until wilted, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{} and mix through the mint and half the @flaked almonds{15%g}. Add a squeeze of @lemon{1} juice to taste. Spoon the couscous into #bowls{} and top with your sausage stew. Finish with the remaining flaked almonds. Enjoy!